'''Wilweorthunga''' is an [[Old English]] word that literally means fountain or well worship. Practised to this day and characterized by tying cloth to trees near wells to will a vow. This belief was banned in the 16th [[Canon Law]] enacted under [[Edgar of England|King Edgar of England]] (939-946) in the [[10th century]].

